I was active in S.D.S. and other anti-war organizations. <br>
I think that part of the anti-vet mentality was due to the <br>
horror we felt about the war and the sence of impotence that<br>
we had. I asked then how could you do something so horrible.<br><br>
I know now that making a choice is often harder to do than<br>
it looks from the outside. At that time I was filled with<br>
contradictory thoughts. On one hand I saw the 'nam vet as<br>
a killer of innocent people, and on the other hand I felt <br>
that vets were in most cases there because they had little<br>
choice or little factual information to make an informed <br>
decision. <br><br>
What we did is now history. What we have to do is learn to <br>
understand both sides, and see the validity of each so that<br>
we can talk openly about what we did, why we did it and learn<br>
from our mistakes to prevent the same mistakes from happening<br>
again. History is doomed to repeat itself if we do not take<br>
the time to learn from others. <br><br>
Jane Fonda went to Hanoi to help end the war and to help save <br>
the lives of American soldiers. You may not think that what<br>
she did helped to accomplish this but it is important<br>
that you understand why she did it.<br><br>
Vets went to Vietnam to help maintain democracy in S.E. Asia<br>
and to prevent the spread of communism. They went to Vietnam<br>
to uphold American honor. You may not agree that this is<br>
what they accomplished but you should accept their motivation<br>
as something that was done for the good of the U.S.<br><br>
If you understand and accept that people did things for good<br>
reasons then it is a lot easier to accept the actions, even if<br>
you do not agree with the outcome.<br><br>
What is honorable is the fact that you did what you thought <br>
was right, even in the face of adversity. For that I honor <br>
and respect the front line soldiers (read vets and protestors)<br>
as well as the Vietnamese who fought and lost far more than<br>
we did.
